Here's the complete implementation:

**Configure request size limits** in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// Allow up to ~11 MB at the server level so your 10 MB app-level check
// has room for multipart overhead.
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 11 * 1024 * 1024);
```

**Add the endpoint** (after `var app = builder.Build();`):

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    const long maxSize = 10L * 1024 * 1024; // 10 MB
    string[] allowed = [".jpg", ".jpeg", ".png"];

    var ext = Path.GetExtension(file.FileName).ToLowerInvariant();

    if (!allowed.Contains(ext))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are accepted.");

    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File size must not exceed 10 MB.");

    var uploads = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploads);

    // Unique name to avoid collisions
    var safeName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{ext}";
    var path = Path.Combine(uploads, safeName);

    await using var stream = File.Create(path);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName = safeName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()          // needed for API clients without a token
.RequestSizeLimit(11_534_336); // per-endpoint override (~11 MB)
```

**Key points:**

- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — since `UseAntiforgery()` is in your pipeline, multipart POSTs from API clients (Postman, mobile apps, etc.) will be rejected unless you explicitly opt out on this endpoint. Remove this call if your clients *do* send antiforgery tokens.
- **`.RequestSizeLimit()`** — overrides the Kestrel default (≈28 MB) or any global `FormOptions` limit on a per-endpoint basis.
- **`Guid` file names** prevent path-traversal attacks and name collisions; the original name is never used on disk.
- Validation runs *before* any disk I/O.
